"'''Better in Time'''" is a [[pop music|pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song performed by British singer [[Leona Lewis]]. It was written by [[J. R. Rotem]] and [[Andrea Martin (musician)|Andrea Martin]], and was produced by Rotem. It is featured on Lewis's debut album [[Spirit (Leona Lewis album)|''Spirit'']] (2007). "Better in Time" was released on 10 March 2008 as Lewis's third single in the United Kingdom, as a [[A-side and B-side#Double A-side|double A-side]] with "[[Footprints in the Sand (song)|Footprints in the Sand]]", and "You Bring Me Down" as B-side. It was Lewis's second international single following her hit "[[Bleeding Love]]" (2007). Lyrically, "Better in Time" tells the story of a girl who cannot forget her ex-partner, and who knows that "it will all get better in time".

Lewis promoted the song on several live television programmes, such as ''[[Good Morning America]]'', ''[[Live with Regis and Kelly]]'', and on the [[American Music Awards of 2008|2008 American Music Awards]], and it was included on the set list of her debut concert tour [[The Labyrinth (tour)|The Labyrinth]] (2010). The music video was filmed by [[Sophie Muller]] at [[Hampton Court House]] School, [[London]] in February 2008. On it, Lewis is shown performing in front of several photographic set-ups, and shows what goes on behind the scenes of them. Receiving generally positive reviews by music critics, it was nominated at the [[Brit Awards]] in the category "Best British Single". "Better in Time" reached number two in the national music charts of the United Kingdom and Germany, as well as the top ten in several countries, including Australia, Canada, Ireland, Italy and New Zealand. The single was [[List of music recording certifications|certified]] gold in Australia, Denmark and Germany, and silver in the UK.

==Composition and release==
{{listen|filename=Betterintime.ogg|title="Better in Time"
|description=A sample of "Better in Time", a [[Pop music|pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song composed in [[G major]], which was described as a song with piano sounds harmonized with Lewis' voice.<ref name="kor"/>
|pos= left
|format=[[Ogg]]}}
"Better in Time" is a [[Pop music|pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song set in [[Time signature|common time]] composed in a moderate [[tempo]] of eighty beats per minute,<ref name="Sheet">Sheet music for "Better in Time". Sony BMG Music Entertainment Publishing (2008).</ref><ref name=sheetbook>{{harvnb|Lewis|2008}}</ref> in the key of [[G flat major]] with a vocal range from the tone of [[C (musical note)|C<sub>4</sub>]] to the note of [[B (musical note)|B<sub>5</sub>]].<ref name="Sheet"/><ref name=sheetbook/> The song has a sequence of G<U+2013>Bm<U+2013>Em<U+2013>G/D<U+2013>C as its chord progression.<ref name="Sheet"/><ref name=sheetbook/> Lyrically the song talks about someone who cannot forget her ex-partner, and at the end the protagonist knows that "it will all get better in time".<ref name="booklet"/> [[Andrea Martin (musician)|Andrea Martin]] and [[J. R. Rotem]] wrote the song, and Rotem composed and produced it.<ref name="booklet"/> On 29 January 2008, Lewis announced on her website that "Better in Time", along with "[[Footprints in the Sand (song)|Footprints in the Sand]]", would be released as a [[A-side and B-side#Double A-side|double A-side]] single on 10 March 2010, as her third single in the United Kingdom,<ref name="announcement"/> with 2008 [[Sport Relief]], a biennial charity organised by [[Comic Relief]] and [[BBC Sport]], selecting "Footprints in the Sand" as their official single.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/music/article898329.ece|work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|publisher=News International |title=Leona Lewis is heading into the top ten again. |date=10 March 2008 |accessdate= 8 September 2010}}</ref><ref name="ama.uk"/><ref name="out today"/> It was also her second international single. A new remix of the song was created for the single release.<ref name="out today">{{cite web |url=http://www.leonalewismusic.co.uk/gb/news/detail/better_in_time_footprints_in_the_sand_out_today/ |title=<U+2018>Better in Time<U+2019> / <U+2018>Footprints in the Sand<U+2019> out today! |accessdate=8 September 2010 |publisher=Leona Lewis Official Website. Sony Music Entertainment |date=10 March 2008}}</ref> The double A-side was released with another song, "You Bring Me Down", as a [[A-side and B-side|B-side]].<ref name="ama.uk"/>

==Critical reception==
[[File:Leona Lewis performing Better in Time-Man Down, Glassheart Tour.jpg|thumbnail|upright|Lewis performing "Better in Time"/"[[Man Down]]" at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] during her 2013 [[Glassheart Tour]].|alt=Three women sing on stage. They wear similar outfit (a dark blouse and trousers).]]
"Better in Time" received generally positive reviews from music critics. In his review of the album, Chung Ah-young of ''[[The Korea Times]]'' described the single as "one of the best tracks [on the album] with impressive [[piano]] sounds harmonized with [Lewis] powerful vocals".<ref name="kor">{{cite news|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2008/01/143_17735.html|title=Album Reviews|publisher=Hankook Ilbo |work=[[The Korea Times]]|date=22 January 2008|accessdate=29 January 2008 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080127071049/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2008/01/143_17735.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 27 January 2008}}</ref> Alex Fletcher from [[Digital Spy]] gave a mixed review to the double A-side. He called the single a "placid affair" with "its plinky-plonky piano and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] groove resting uncomfortably next to Lewis's creamy vocal style".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a90538/leona-lewis-better-in-time--footprints-in-the-sand.html|title=Leona Lewis: 'Better in Time' / 'Footprints in the Sand' |publisher=Digital Spy. Hachette Filipacchi Ltd|first=Alex|last=Fletcher|accessdate=28 August 2010 |date=10 March 2010}}</ref> The [[BBC]]'s reviewer Fraser McAlpine gave "Better in Time" three stars our of five commenting that "The tune's quite nice, fairly hummable without ever actually going anywhere and despite the floaty, [[Mariah Carey|Mariah]]-esque qualities of Leona's vocals, it never goes completely mental in the throat-breakdancing department".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/chartblog/2008/03/leona_lewis_better_in_time.shtml|title=Leona Lewis <U+2013> 'Better In Time'|publisher=BBC|date=6 March 2008|accessdate=8 March 2008}}</ref> Chuck Taylor of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' gave a positive review, stating that the song is of "equal caliber to its predecessor ["[[Bleeding Love]]"], with a one-listen hook, elegant chug-along melody, a lyric about healing and Lewis' unquestionably emotive vocal versatility".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Singles |page=46 |last=Taylor|first=Chuck|date=19 July 2008|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Company|issn=00062510|ref=harv}}</ref> Sarah Rodman of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' called it a "{{'}}love takes time' rumination", and along with another song of the album ("[[I Will Be]]"), described it as "predictable".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/music/cd_reviews/articles/2008/04/08/lewiss_huge_voice_lifts_spirit/ |work=The Boston Globe |publisher=The New York Times Company |first=Sarah |last=Rodman |date= 8 April 2008 |accessdate= 28 August 2010 |title=Lewis's huge voice lifts 'Spirit'}}</ref> Sean Fennessey for ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' noted that the track "is the best thing [on the album], is mannered and takes nearly three minutes to get off the ground".<ref>{{cite journal | title=Leona Lewis <U+2013> Spirit |work=Vibe |publisher=Time Inc |first=Sean |last=Fennessey |date=June 2008 |issn=10704701|page=66 | ref=harv}}</ref> It ranked at number four on the "10 Best Singles of 2008" list by American magazine ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20162677_20164091_20247335_6,00.html
|title=10 Best Singles of 2008|date=18 December 2008|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=Time Inc|accessdate=28 August 2010}}</ref> "Better in Time" was nominated at the [[2009 BRIT Awards]] in the category of Best British Single,<ref>{{cite news |publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 August 2010 |title=Brit Awards 2009: Winners list |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7841069.stm |date=20 January 2009}}</ref> and later the song was included on the awards' compilation album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amazon.com/dp/B002LCEXP8 |publisher=Amazon United States. Amazon Inc |accessdate=30 August 2010 |title=Music From Brit Awards 2009 Volume 1}}</ref>

==Chart performance==
[[File:Leona Lewis 2009 VH1 Divas.jpg|Lewis on the red carpet of the 2009 [[VH1 Divas]].|left|upright|alt=A woman is standing up. She is wearing a long pink dress with a black corset. She is holding her hands in front of her body.|thumb]]
The double A-side "Better in Time" and "Footprints in the Sand" debuted at number seventy-four on the [[UK Singles Chart]] on 1 March  2008; rising thirty-six places, it debuted in the top forty the following week, at number thirty-eight.<ref name="chst">{{cite web|url=http://www.chartstats.com/songinfo.php?id=33689 |title=Chart Stats - Leona Lewis - Better in Time/Fooprnts in the Sand|publisher=Chart Stats|work=The Official UK Charts Company|accessdate=17 May 2010}}</ref> On its fourth week, the song reached its peak position at number two, selling 40,476 copies and being beaten to the number one spot by [[Duffy (singer)|Duffy]]'s "[[Mercy (Duffy song)|Mercy]]".<ref>{{cite web|title=Did Duffy win fair and square?|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storycode=1033556|publisher=Music Week|date=17 March 2008|accessdate=30 August 2010 |last=Jones |first=Alan }}</ref> With this it became the third single by Lewis to reach the top five in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chartstats.com/artistinfo.php?id=10886 |title=Charts Stats - Leona Lewis |accessdate=31 August 2010 |publisher=Chart Stats. The Official Charts Company}}</ref> "Better in Time" and "Footprints in the Sand" was certified as silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI).<ref name="BPI"/><ref name="Y-E"/> In the [[ARIA Charts|Australian charts]], "Better in Time" debuted at number thirty-two on 27 April 2008, reaching the top ten two weeks later, her second single to achieve this feat.<ref name="aust"/> On 25 May 2008 the single reached its peak position, at number six, and remained within the top fifty for eighteen weeks.<ref name="aust"/> The song was later certified gold by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA).<ref name="ariaaccre"/> It debuted at number thirty-four on New Zealand's [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|RIANZ]] Chart on 17 March 2008, eventually reaching number nine after five weeks, and by its seventh week had climbed to number six, thereby becoming her second consecutive top ten hit in the country.<ref name="newze"/> "Better in Time" and "Footprints in the Sand" debuted in the [[Media Control Charts|German charts]] on 16 June 2008 at number five. Although it fell out the top ten the following week, it managed to reach the top five in the issue ending 27 July 2010, and rose to its peak position, at number two, in subsequent days.<ref name="gerpre"/> "Better in Time" entered the German chart on 22 February 2009 at number seventy-nine, where it stayed for three weeks.<ref name="gerbas"/> It achieved a gold certification by the [[Bundesverband Musikindustrie]] (BVMI).<ref name="certger"/> In [[Tracklisten|Denmark]] "Better in Time" entered  the charts at number twenty-nine on 9 May 2008, and managed to rise twenty-three places in the next two weeks. On 6 June 2008 the single reached its peak position, number three. Next week, it fell out two places, but it retook its peak the following issue, and the song continued in this position for three weeks.<ref name="den"/> <!--Later the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI) certified the single as gold.<ref name="dencert">{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.dk/index.php?pk_menu=261|title=IFPI Danmark <U+2013> 2008 |publisher=International Federation of the Phonographic Industry |accessdate=30 August 2010 |language=Danish}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>-->

"Better in Time" and "Footprints in the Sand" debuted and peaked at number eight on the [[European Hot 100 Singles]] in the issue ending 29 March 2008, becoming the highest debut of the week.<ref name="euro">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/european-hot-100?chartDate=2008-08-02#/charts/european-hot-100?chartDate=2008-03-29&order=gainer |title=Week of March 29, 2008 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Company |date=29 March 2008 |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref> Moreover, "Better in Time" was also a success in the chart, the single eventually reached number seven on the chart in the week ending 2 August 2008.<ref name="billusa"/> In [[Swiss Music Charts|Switzerland]], the single entered at number thirteen, becoming the highest release of the week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Leona+Lewis&titel=Better+In+Time&cat=s |title=Leona Lewis - Better In Time |accessdate=1 September 2010 |publisher=Hung Medien }}</ref> On 27 July 2008, its ninth week, it reached its peak position at number five, becoming Lewis's second top five in the country. It managed to stay within the top ten for eleven weeks and it was last seen in the chart on 22 March 2009, forty-two weeks after its debut.<ref name="switch"/> In the week ending 26 April 2008, "Better in Time" debuted at number sixty-two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-04-26/hot-100?order=gainer |title=Week of April 26, 2008 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Company |date=26 April 2008 |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref> in the same week that her previous single, "Bleeding Love", topped the chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-04-26/hot-100?order=position |title=Week of April 26, 2008 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Company |date=26 April 2008 |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref> Next week it dropped out of the chart but later re-entered the Hot 100 at number seventy-five, becoming the best comeback of the week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-08-02/hot-100 |title=Week of August 2, 2008 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Company |date=2 August 2008 |accessdate=1 September 2010}}</ref> The song reached its peak position at number eleven on its fourteenth week, where it stayed for another week.<ref name="billusa"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://acharts.us/song/34178 |publisher=<U+03B1>Charts.us |accessdate=1 September 2010 |title=Leona Lewis - Better in Time}}</ref> In other charts of the United States, "Better in Time" peaked at number four on the [[Adult Top 40]],<ref name="billusa"/> ninety-nine on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]],<ref name="billusa"/> three at the [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|Mainstream Top 40]],<ref name="billusa"/> and at number four on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary chart]], where it spent fifty-two weeks on the chart.<ref name="billusa"/><ref>{{cite web|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Company|title=Week of October 24, 2009 |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2009-10-24/adult-contemporary |date=24 October 2009 |accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref> The single became the seventeenth best-selling single of 2008 in Austria,<ref name="austend"/> as well as the twenty-second in Germany and Switzerland,<ref name="germ_end"/><ref name="swissend"/> the thirty-sixth in New Zealand,<ref name="newzeaend"/> the thirty-seventh in the UK,<ref name="Y-E"/> the fifty-fifth of Australia,<ref name="AUSendofyear"/> the sixty-fourth in the Netherlands,<ref name="dutchend"/> and the seventy-second in Flanders, a region in Belgium.<ref name="flandend"/>

==Music video and promotion==
[[File:Better in Time video.jpg|thumb|right|220px|The music video shows Lewis performing in front of several photographic sessions.|alt=The black-and-white portrait of a brunnete woman, who is sitting in a chair. She is wearing a black sweater and jeans. In front of her, two men, one standing up, and the second taking photos are observable.]]
The [[music video]] was filmed at [[Hampton Court House]] School in [[London]] by the British director [[Sophie Muller]] in February 2008,<ref name="video1">{{cite web |date=21 February 2008 |title=Behind-the-scenes on 'Better in Time' shoot |url=http://www.leonalewismusic.co.uk/gb/news/detail/behind_the_scenes_on_better_in_time_shoot/ |accessdate=3 September 2010|publisher=Leona Lewis Official Website. Sony Music Entertainment}}</ref> and was released at the end of the same month.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leonalewismusic.co.uk/gb/news/detail/better_in_time_video/ |title=Better in Time video |accessdate=3 September 2010|publisher=Leona Lewis Official Website. Sony Music Entertainment |date=29 February 2008}}</ref> The video is inspired by fashion design, with Lewis performing in front of "unrelated photographic set-ups", and shows what goes on behind the scenes.<ref name="bbcnews">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7245446.stm|title=Lewis makes footprints in States |publisher=BBC News. BBC|first=Liam|last=Allen|date=15 February 2008|accessdate=17 February 2008}}</ref> In some parts of the video Lewis is shown with a [[horse]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/fame/article.html?in_article_id=99220&in_page_id=7|title=Leona saddles up for chart success|publisher=Associated Newspapers |work=Metro|first=Andrei|last=Harmsworth|date=15 February 2008|accessdate=17 February 2008}}</ref>

Lewis first performed the song live on the television programme ''[[Dancing on Ice (UK)|Dancing on Ice]]'' on 9 March 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/article859358.ece|title=Leona Lewis' blades of glory|work=The Sun|publisher=News International|date=29 February 2008|accessdate=29 February 2008}}</ref> Lewis also performed both sides of the single on [[BBC One]]'s Sport Relief on 14 March 2008,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tv_and_radio/7802107.stm |title=Rise to the challenge for Sport Relief |publisher=BBC Sports. BBC|accessdate=7 September 2010 |date=28 December 2008}}</ref> ''[[Good Morning America]]'' on 4 April 2008,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Good Morning America |network=[[American Broadcasting Company]] |series=Good Morning America |serieslink=Good Morning America |accessdate=7 September 2010 }}</ref> and on the ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' show along with "Bleeding Love".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Jimmy Kimmel Live! |accessdate=7 September 2010 |series=Jimmy Kimmel Live! |serieslink=Jimmy Kimmel Live! |network=American Broadcasting Company}}</ref> On 3 September 2008 Lewis performed the song on ''[[Live with Regis and Kelly]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/regisandkelly/special/livestage/index.html |work=Live with Regis and Kelly |publisher=American Broadcasting Company |accessdate=7 September 2010 |date=3 September 2008 |title=The Live Stage}}</ref> and on 1 October 2008 on the season finale of ''[[America's Got Talent (season 3)|America's Got Talent]]''.<ref>{{cite episode | title = Finale Results |series=America's Got Talent |serieslink= America's Got Talent (season 3) |airdate= 1 October 2008|season=3 |number=20 |accessdate=7 September 2010}}</ref> The song was featured in the ''[[90210 (TV series)|90210]]'' episode "Lucky Strike", originally aired on 9 September 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv.com/90210/lucky-strike/episode/1225889/summary.html |publisher=TV.com. CBS Interactive
|accessdate=8 September 2010 |title=90210: Lucky Strike}}</ref> On 24 November 2008, Lewis performed the song at the [[American Music Awards of 2008|2008 American Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE49T3CG20081030 |title=Leona Lewis to join American Music Awards |date=30 October 2010 |accessdate=8 September 2010 |publisher=Reuters |work=Billboard}}</ref> In May 2010, the song was added to the setlist of her [[The Labyrinth (tour)|The Labyrinth]] tour, performed as the fourth song of the show.<ref name="tour">{{cite web|url=http://www.leonalewismusic.co.uk/gb/news/detail/the_labyrinth_live_tour_dvd/|title=The Labyrinth Live Tour DVD |date=9 November 2010 |work=Leona Lewis Official Website|publisher= Sony Music Entertainment|accessdate=17 November 2010}}</ref> "Better in Time" was included on the tour's live album and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] ''The Labyrinth Tour Live from The O2'', released on 29 November 2010.<ref name="tour" /> In 2011, Lewis performed a [[reggae]] version of the song at [[BBC Radio 1]] segment [[Live Lounge]], where she [[Mashup (music)|mashed up]] the single with "[[Man Down]]", a song by [[Rihanna]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sony Music UK. Sony Music Entertainment|date=23 May 2011|accessdate=24 May 2011|title=Leona performs Reggae version of 'Better In Time' / Rihanna's 'Man Down' in the Radio 1 Live Lounge|url=http://www.sonymusic.co.uk/news/20409/0/}}</ref> It is also one of thirty-eight songs included on the benefit album ''[[Songs for Japan]]'', a compilation album released in response to the aftermath of the [[2011 T<U+014D>hoku earthquake and tsunami|2011 earthquake and tsunami in T<U+014D>hoku, Japan]]), released on 25 March 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1660688/songs-japan-includes-eminem-justin-bieber-lady-gaga-more.jhtml|title=Songs For Japan Includes Eminem, Justin Bieber, Lady Gaga And More|last=Montgomery|first=James|date=25 March 2011|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=[[MTV|MTV News]]. [[Viacom|Viacom Inc.]]}}</ref> "Better in Time" was used in the American television series [[Pretty Little Liars (TV series)|''Pretty Little Liars'']], for the [[Pretty Little Liars (season 2)|second season]] finale "unmAsked", in the [[masquerade ball]] scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jaimie-etkin/pretty-little-liars-recap_4_b_1369003.html|title='Pretty Little Liars' Recap: Season 2 Finale Gets 'Psycho' With Mona|first=
Jaimie|last=Etkin|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=30 December 2012|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|publisher=[[AOL|AOL Inc]]}}</ref> In 2013, Lewis performed the song along with "Man Down" during her [[Glassheart Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Corner|first=Lewis|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a473838/leona-lewis-begins-glassheart-tour-in-germany-pictures.html|title=Leona Lewis begins 'Glassheart' tour in Germany - pictures|publisher=Digital Spy. Hachette Filipacchi UK|date=17 April 2013|accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref>

